[36m│[0m [BEGIN context from                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m [superpowers/test-driven-development/testing-anti-patterns]]                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m # Testing Anti-Patterns                                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Load this reference when:** writing or changing tests, adding mocks, or   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m tempted to add test-only methods to production code.                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Overview                                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Tests must verify real behavior, not mock behavior. Mocks are a means to    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m isolate, not the thing being tested.                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Core principle:** Test what the code does, not what the mocks do.         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Following strict TDD prevents these anti-patterns.**                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## The Iron Laws                                                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 1. NEVER test mock behavior                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 2. NEVER add test-only methods to production classes                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 3. NEVER mock without understanding dependencies                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Anti-Pattern 1: Testing Mock Behavior                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The violation:**                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```typescript                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // ❌ BAD: Testing that the mock exists                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m test('renders sidebar', () => {                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   render(<Page />);                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   expect(screen.getByTestId('sidebar-mock')).toBeInTheDocument();           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m });                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Why this is wrong:**                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - You're verifying the mock works, not that the component works             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Test passes when mock is present, fails when it's not                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Tells you nothing about real behavior                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **your human partner's correction:** "Are we testing the behavior of a      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m mock?"                                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The fix:**                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```typescript                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // ✅ GOOD: Test real component or don't mock it                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m test('renders sidebar', () => {                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   render(<Page />);  // Don't mock sidebar                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   expect(screen.getByRole('navigation')).toBeInTheDocument();               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m });                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // OR if sidebar must be mocked for isolation:                              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // Don't assert on the mock - test Page's behavior with sidebar present     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Gate Function                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m BEFORE asserting on any mock element:                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   Ask: "Am I testing real component behavior or just mock existence?"       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   IF testing mock existence:                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     STOP - Delete the assertion or unmock the component                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   Test real behavior instead                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Anti-Pattern 2: Test-Only Methods in Production                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The violation:**                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```typescript                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // ❌ BAD: destroy() only used in tests                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m class Session {                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   async destroy() {  // Looks like production API!                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     await this._workspaceManager?.destroyWorkspace(this.id);                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     // ... cleanup                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   }                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m }                                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // In tests                                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m afterEach(() => session.destroy());                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Why this is wrong:**                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Production class polluted with test-only code                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Dangerous if accidentally called in production                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Violates YAGNI and separation of concerns                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Confuses object lifecycle with entity lifecycle                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The fix:**                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```typescript                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // ✅ GOOD: Test utilities handle test cleanup                              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // Session has no destroy() - it's stateless in production                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // In test-utils/                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m export async function cleanupSession(session: Session) {                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   const workspace = session.getWorkspaceInfo();                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   if (workspace) {                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     await workspaceManager.destroyWorkspace(workspace.id);                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   }                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m }                                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // In tests                                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m afterEach(() => cleanupSession(session));                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Gate Function                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m BEFORE adding any method to production class:                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   Ask: "Is this only used by tests?"                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   IF yes:                                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     STOP - Don't add it                                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     Put it in test utilities instead                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   Ask: "Does this class own this resource's lifecycle?"                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   IF no:                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     STOP - Wrong class for this method                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Anti-Pattern 3: Mocking Without Understanding                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The violation:**                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```typescript                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // ❌ BAD: Mock breaks test logic                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m test('detects duplicate server', () => {                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   // Mock prevents config write that test depends on!                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   vi.mock('ToolCatalog', () => ({                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     discoverAndCacheTools: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined)             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   }));                                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   await addServer(config);                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   await addServer(config);  // Should throw - but won't!                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m });                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Why this is wrong:**                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Mocked method had side effect test depended on (writing config)           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Over-mocking to "be safe" breaks actual behavior                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Test passes for wrong reason or fails mysteriously                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The fix:**                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```typescript                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // ✅ GOOD: Mock at correct level                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m test('detects duplicate server', () => {                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   // Mock the slow part, preserve behavior test needs                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   vi.mock('MCPServerManager'); // Just mock slow server startup             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   await addServer(config);  // Config written                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   await addServer(config);  // Duplicate detected ✓                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m });                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Gate Function                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m BEFORE mocking any method:                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   STOP - Don't mock yet                                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   1. Ask: "What side effects does the real method have?"                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   2. Ask: "Does this test depend on any of those side effects?"             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   3. Ask: "Do I fully understand what this test needs?"                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   IF depends on side effects:                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     Mock at lower level (the actual slow/external operation)                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     OR use test doubles that preserve necessary behavior                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     NOT the high-level method the test depends on                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   IF unsure what test depends on:                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     Run test with real implementation FIRST                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     Observe what actually needs to happen                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     THEN add minimal mocking at the right level                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   Red flags:                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     - "I'll mock this to be safe"                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     - "This might be slow, better mock it"                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     - Mocking without understanding the dependency chain                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Anti-Pattern 4: Incomplete Mocks                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The violation:**                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```typescript                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // ❌ BAD: Partial mock - only fields you think you need                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m const mockResponse = {                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   status: 'success',                                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   data: { userId: '123', name: 'Alice' }                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   // Missing: metadata that downstream code uses                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m };                                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // Later: breaks when code accesses response.metadata.requestId             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Why this is wrong:**                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - **Partial mocks hide structural assumptions** - You only mocked fields    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m you know about                                                              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - **Downstream code may depend on fields you didn't include** - Silent      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m failures                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - **Tests pass but integration fails** - Mock incomplete, real API complete [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - **False confidence** - Test proves nothing about real behavior            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The Iron Rule:** Mock the COMPLETE data structure as it exists in         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m reality, not just fields your immediate test uses.                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The fix:**                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```typescript                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m // ✅ GOOD: Mirror real API completeness                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m const mockResponse = {                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   status: 'success',                                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   data: { userId: '123', name: 'Alice' },                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   metadata: { requestId: 'req-789', timestamp: 1234567890 }                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   // All fields real API returns                                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m };                                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Gate Function                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m BEFORE creating mock responses:                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   Check: "What fields does the real API response contain?"                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   Actions:                                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     1. Examine actual API response from docs/examples                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     2. Include ALL fields system might consume downstream                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     3. Verify mock matches real response schema completely                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   Critical:                                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     If you're creating a mock, you must understand the ENTIRE structure     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     Partial mocks fail silently when code depends on omitted fields         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   If uncertain: Include all documented fields                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Anti-Pattern 5: Integration Tests as Afterthought                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The violation:**                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ✅ Implementation complete                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ❌ No tests written                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m "Ready for testing"                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Why this is wrong:**                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Testing is part of implementation, not optional follow-up                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - TDD would have caught this                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Can't claim complete without tests                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **The fix:**                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m TDD cycle:                                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 1. Write failing test                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 2. Implement to pass                                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 3. Refactor                                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 4. THEN claim complete                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## When Mocks Become Too Complex                                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Warning signs:**                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Mock setup longer than test logic                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Mocking everything to make test pass                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Mocks missing methods real components have                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Test breaks when mock changes                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **your human partner's question:** "Do we need to be using a mock here?"    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Consider:** Integration tests with real components often simpler than     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m complex mocks                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## TDD Prevents These Anti-Patterns                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Why TDD helps:**                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 1. **Write test first** → Forces you to think about what you're actually    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m testing                                                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 2. **Watch it fail** → Confirms test tests real behavior, not mocks         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 3. **Minimal implementation** → No test-only methods creep in               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 4. **Real dependencies** → You see what the test actually needs before      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m mocking                                                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **If you're testing mock behavior, you violated TDD** - you added mocks     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m without watching test fail against real code first.                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Quick Reference                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m | Anti-Pattern | Fix |                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m |--------------|-----|                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m | Assert on mock elements | Test real component or unmock it |              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m | Test-only methods in production | Move to test utilities |                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m | Mock without understanding | Understand dependencies first, mock          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m minimally |                                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m | Incomplete mocks | Mirror real API completely |                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m | Tests as afterthought | TDD - tests first |                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m | Over-complex mocks | Consider integration tests |                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Red Flags                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Assertion checks for `*-mock` test IDs                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Methods only called in test files                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Mock setup is >50% of test                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Test fails when you remove mock                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Can't explain why mock is needed                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m - Mocking "just to be safe"                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## The Bottom Line                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Mocks are tools to isolate, not things to test.**                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m If TDD reveals you're testing mock behavior, you've gone wrong.             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Fix: Test real behavior or question why you're mocking at all.              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m [END Context]                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m [BEGIN context from                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m [superpowers/writing-plans/plan-document-reviewer-prompt]]                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m # Plan Document Reviewer Prompt Template                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Use this template when dispatching a plan document reviewer subagent.       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Purpose:** Verify the plan is complete, matches the spec, and has proper  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m task decomposition.                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Dispatch after:** The complete plan is written.                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Task tool (general-purpose):                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   description: "Review plan document"                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   prompt: |                                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     You are a plan document reviewer. Verify this plan is complete and      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ready for implementation.                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     **Plan to review:** [PLAN_FILE_PATH]                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     **Spec for reference:** [SPEC_FILE_PATH]                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     ## What to Check                                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     | Category | What to Look For |                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     |----------|------------------|                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     | Completeness | TODOs, placeholders, incomplete tasks, missing steps | [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     | Spec Alignment | Plan covers spec requirements, no major scope creep  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m |                                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     | Task Decomposition | Tasks have clear boundaries, steps are           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m actionable |                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     | Buildability | Could an engineer follow this plan without getting     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m stuck? |                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     ## Calibration                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     **Only flag issues that would cause real problems during                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m implementation.**                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     An implementer building the wrong thing or getting stuck is an issue.   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     Minor wording, stylistic preferences, and "nice to have" suggestions    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m are not.                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     Approve unless there are serious gaps — missing requirements from the   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m spec,                                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     contradictory steps, placeholder content, or tasks so vague they can't  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m be acted on.                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     ## Output Format                                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     ## Plan Review                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     **Status:** Approved | Issues Found                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     **Issues (if any):**                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     - [Task X, Step Y]: [specific issue] - [why it matters for              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m implementation]                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     **Recommendations (advisory, do not block approval):**                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     - [suggestions for improvement]                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Reviewer returns:** Status, Issues (if any), Recommendations              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m [END Context]                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m [BEGIN context from [superpowers/writing-skills/anthropic-best-practices]]  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m # Skill authoring best practices                                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m > Learn how to write effective Skills that Claude can discover and use      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m successfully.                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Good Skills are concise, well-structured, and tested with real usage. This  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m guide provides practical authoring decisions to help you write Skills that  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Claude can discover and use effectively.                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m For conceptual background on how Skills work, see the [Skills               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m overview](/en/docs/agents-and-tools/agent-skills/overview).                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Core principles                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Concise is key                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m The [context                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m window](https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/context-windo [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ws) is a public good. Your Skill shares the context window with everything  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m else Claude needs to know, including:                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * The system prompt                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Conversation history                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Other Skills' metadata                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Your actual request                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Not every token in your Skill has an immediate cost. At startup, only the   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m metadata (name and description) from all Skills is pre-loaded. Claude reads [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m SKILL.md only when the Skill becomes relevant, and reads additional files   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m only as needed. However, being concise in SKILL.md still matters: once      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Claude loads it, every token competes with conversation history and other   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m context.                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Default assumption**: Claude is already very smart                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Only add context Claude doesn't already have. Challenge each piece of       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m information:                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * "Does Claude really need this explanation?"                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * "Can I assume Claude knows this?"                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * "Does this paragraph justify its token cost?"                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Good example: Concise** (approximately 50 tokens):                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ````markdown  theme={null}                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Extract PDF text                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Use pdfplumber for text extraction:                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```python                                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m import pdfplumber                                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m with pdfplumber.open("file.pdf") as pdf:                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     text = pdf.pages[0].extract_text()                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ````                                                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Bad example: Too verbose** (approximately 150 tokens):                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```markdown  theme={null}                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Extract PDF text                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m PDF (Portable Document Format) files are a common file format that contains [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m text, images, and other content. To extract text from a PDF, you'll need to [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m use a library. There are many libraries available for PDF processing, but   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m we                                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m recommend pdfplumber because it's easy to use and handles most cases well.  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m First, you'll need to install it using pip. Then you can use the code       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m below...                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m The concise version assumes Claude knows what PDFs are and how libraries    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m work.                                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Set appropriate degrees of freedom                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Match the level of specificity to the task's fragility and variability.     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **High freedom** (text-based instructions):                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Use when:                                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Multiple approaches are valid                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Decisions depend on context                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Heuristics guide the approach                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Example:                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```markdown  theme={null}                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Code review process                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 1. Analyze the code structure and organization                              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 2. Check for potential bugs or edge cases                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 3. Suggest improvements for readability and maintainability                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m 4. Verify adherence to project conventions                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Medium freedom** (pseudocode or scripts with parameters):                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Use when:                                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * A preferred pattern exists                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Some variation is acceptable                                              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Configuration affects behavior                                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Example:                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ````markdown  theme={null}                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Generate report                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Use this template and customize as needed:                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```python                                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m def generate_report(data, format="markdown", include_charts=True):          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     # Process data                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     # Generate output in specified format                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m     # Optionally include visualizations                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ````                                                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Low freedom** (specific scripts, few or no parameters):                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Use when:                                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Operations are fragile and error-prone                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Consistency is critical                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * A specific sequence must be followed                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Example:                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ````markdown  theme={null}                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Database migration                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Run exactly this script:                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```powershell                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m python scripts/migrate.py --verify --backup                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Do not modify the command or add additional flags.                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ````                                                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Analogy**: Think of Claude as a robot exploring a path:                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * **Narrow bridge with cliffs on both sides**: There's only one safe way    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m forward. Provide specific guardrails and exact instructions (low freedom).  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Example: database migrations that must run in exact sequence.               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * **Open field with no hazards**: Many paths lead to success. Give general  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m direction and trust Claude to find the best route (high freedom). Example:  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m code reviews where context determines the best approach.                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Test with all models you plan to use                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Skills act as additions to models, so effectiveness depends on the          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m underlying model. Test your Skill with all the models you plan to use it    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m with.                                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Testing considerations by model**:                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * **Claude Haiku** (fast, economical): Does the Skill provide enough        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m guidance?                                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * **Claude Sonnet** (balanced): Is the Skill clear and efficient?           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * **Claude Opus** (powerful reasoning): Does the Skill avoid                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m over-explaining?                                                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m What works perfectly for Opus might need more detail for Haiku. If you plan [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m to use your Skill across multiple models, aim for instructions that work    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m well with all of them.                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ## Skill structure                                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m <Note>                                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   **YAML Frontmatter**: The SKILL.md frontmatter requires two fields:       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   * `name` - Human-readable name of the Skill (64 characters maximum)       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   * `description` - One-line description of what the Skill does and when to [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m use it (1024 characters maximum)                                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   For complete Skill structure details, see the [Skills                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m overview](/en/docs/agents-and-tools/agent-skills/overview#skill-structure). [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m </Note>                                                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Naming conventions                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Use consistent naming patterns to make Skills easier to reference and       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m discuss. We recommend using **gerund form** (verb + -ing) for Skill names,  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m as this clearly describes the activity or capability the Skill provides.    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Good naming examples (gerund form)**:                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * "Processing PDFs"                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * "Analyzing spreadsheets"                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * "Managing databases"                                                      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * "Testing code"                                                            [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * "Writing documentation"                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Acceptable alternatives**:                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Noun phrases: "PDF Processing", "Spreadsheet Analysis"                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Action-oriented: "Process PDFs", "Analyze Spreadsheets"                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Avoid**:                                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Vague names: "Helper", "Utils", "Tools"                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Overly generic: "Documents", "Data", "Files"                              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Inconsistent patterns within your skill collection                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Consistent naming makes it easier to:                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Reference Skills in documentation and conversations                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Understand what a Skill does at a glance                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Organize and search through multiple Skills                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Maintain a professional, cohesive skill library                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Writing effective descriptions                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m The `description` field enables Skill discovery and should include both     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m what the Skill does and when to use it.                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m <Warning>                                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   **Always write in third person**. The description is injected into the    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m system prompt, and inconsistent point-of-view can cause discovery problems. [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   * **Good:** "Processes Excel files and generates reports"                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   * **Avoid:** "I can help you process Excel files"                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m   * **Avoid:** "You can use this to process Excel files"                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m </Warning>                                                                  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Be specific and include key terms**. Include both what the Skill does and [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m specific triggers/contexts for when to use it.                              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Each Skill has exactly one description field. The description is critical   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m for skill selection: Claude uses it to choose the right Skill from          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m potentially 100+ available Skills. Your description must provide enough     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m detail for Claude to know when to select this Skill, while the rest of      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m SKILL.md provides the implementation details.                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Effective examples:                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **PDF Processing skill:**                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```yaml  theme={null}                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m description: Extract text and tables from PDF files, fill forms, merge      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m documents. Use when working with PDF files or when the user mentions PDFs,  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m forms, or document extraction.                                              [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Excel Analysis skill:**                                                   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```yaml  theme={null}                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m description: Analyze Excel spreadsheets, create pivot tables, generate      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m charts. Use when analyzing Excel files, spreadsheets, tabular data, or      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m .xlsx files.                                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Git Commit Helper skill:**                                                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```yaml  theme={null}                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m description: Generate descriptive commit messages by analyzing git diffs.   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Use when the user asks for help writing commit messages or reviewing staged [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m changes.                                                                    [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m Avoid vague descriptions like these:                                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```yaml  theme={null}                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m description: Helps with documents                                           [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```yaml  theme={null}                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m description: Processes data                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```yaml  theme={null}                                                       [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m description: Does stuff with files                                          [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ```                                                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m ### Progressive disclosure patterns                                         [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m SKILL.md serves as an overview that points Claude to detailed materials as  [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m needed, like a table of contents in an onboarding guide. For an explanation [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m of how progressive disclosure works, see [How Skills                        [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m work](/en/docs/agents-and-tools/agent-skills/overview#how-skills-work) in   [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m the overview.                                                               [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m **Practical guidance:**                                                     [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Keep SKILL.md body under 500 lines for optimal performance                [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Split content into separate files when approaching this limit             [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m * Use the patterns below to organize instructions, code, and resources      [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m effectively                                                                 [36m│[0m
[36m│[0m                                                                             [36m│[0m
